students <- read.csv("data/students.csv")

visualise frequency of superpower

students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower)) +
  geom_bar()

colour?

fill in the geom parts –the main part of the area colour in geom is the outline colour

students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "light blue",
           colour = "red")


students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower,
             fill = school_year)) +
  geom_bar()

Position adjustments

students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower,
             fill = school_year)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")

statistical transformations

students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower,
             fill = school_year))+
  geom_bar(stat = "count")

count_data <- students %>% 
  group_by(superpower, school_year) %>% 
  summarise(count = n())
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'superpower'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
count_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower, y = count, fill = school_year)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

count_data %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower, y = count, fill = school_year)) +
  geom_col()

labels for new lines

students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = superpower,
             fill = school_year)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(x = "\nSuperpower",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Perferred superpower bu school year",
       subtitle = "Data from students around the world\n",
       fill = "School Year")

Go back to using the students dataset:

1,Use geom_point to make a scatter graph, with the height of students on the x-axis and their reaction time of the y axis.

2,Make all the points blue. For geom_bar, the colour of the bar is controlled by fill, but for geom_point the colour of the points are controlled by colour.

3,Make the colour of the points depend on the superpower the student wishes they had.

4,Write down what the graph tells you overall.

students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height_cm, 
         y = reaction_time
         ))+
  geom_point(colour = "blue")+
  labs(x = "\nHeight",
       y = "Reaction time",
       title = "Heigh-Reaction chart\n")

#No correlations here, everyone seems to have similar reaction time 
students %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = height_cm, 
         y = reaction_time,
         colour = superpower))+
  geom_point()+
    labs(x = "\nHeight",
       y = "Reaction time",
       title = "Heigh-Reaction chart",
       fill = "Superpower",
       subtitle = "Coloured by superpower preferred\n")

Create a labelled scatter plot, of pet age vs. weight, with the following 5 mapping/aesthetics. For items 3-5 you may want to look at the help file of ?geom_point and read about different aesthetics:

1.We want age on the x-axis and weight on the y axis 2.We want the points to be different colours depending on the gender of the pet 3.We want different shapes depending on the type of animal 4.We want all the points to be bigger than normal (size 4). 5.We also want labels with the pets names next to every point.

pets %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age,
         y = weight,
         colour = sex
         ))+
  geom_point(aes(shape = animal),
             alpha = 0.5,
             size = 4) +
  geom_text(aes(label = name),
            hjust=0, vjust=0)+
  labs(x = "Age",
       y = "Weight",
       title = "Weight-Age of pets")
